Charles Czeisler, sleep medicine professor at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the one who created the course, which is believed to be the first of this guy in the United States.
It was inspired to create the course after holding a conference on the impact of sleeplessness on the ability to learn.
"In the end, a girl came and said to me, "Why is this just now, in the last year?"
She told me that she never talked to her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he said for The Telegraph.
The course, introduced first this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits help to improve academic and athletic performance, as well as the general good condition.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of health services at the university, said that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were seriously sleepless during the week.
The one-hour course may involve a series of interactive tasks.
Within a section is presented the image of a room of home, and students can click on coffee cans, curtains, sports pants and books to tell them what the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deficiency, but also about the importance of a sleep program.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive pictograms, encourages participants to think about their daily program.
"We know that we can't change student behavior instantly.
But we believe that they have the right to know, just as anyone has the right to know what the effects of smoking are on health," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture that makes students proud that they have learned all night still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure imposed on students have turned sleep deprivation into an increasing problem.
The sufficient sleep, of good quality, should be a "secret weapon" of a student to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation makes the brain believe that the body is hungry, which makes the students feel that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student in California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler create the course after he took part in one of his first years at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course for all students.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all post-university students to complete a similar curriculum of studies before joining this institution where competition is acute.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students schedule an alarm to know when it is time to go to bed, as well as for waking hours, and to know what the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LEDs, which can disrupt circadian rhythm and cause difficulties when they try to sleep.
