A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to "detect" harmful cells
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to "detect" and destroy harmful cells
As part of the treatment, the vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize harmful cells
The method involves extracting immune cells from a patient, altering them in a laboratory
They can "detect" a common protein of many cancers and then are reinjected
A test vaccine provides promising results for patients with a range of cancers.
The ovarian cancer of a woman treated with the vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize harmful cells has disappeared for more than 18 months.
The method involves extracting the immune cells from a patient, altering them in the laboratory so that they can "detect" a common protein of many cancers, called HER2, then reinjecting cells.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Institute of Oncology in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results suggest that we have to deal with a very promising vaccine."
HER2 "determines the growth of several types of cancers", including breast, ovaries, pulmonary and colorectal, explained Professor Berzofsky.
A similar approach, to remove the immune cells from patients and to “teach” them to target cancer cells, has also worked to treat a type of leukaemia.
