What is the Global Citizens' Festival and has it managed to do something to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, New York will host the Global Citizen's Festival, an annual musical event in which an impressive group of stars will participate, with a equally impressive mission: the elimination of world poverty.
In addition to the seventh edition, the Global Citizen Festival will attract tens of thousands of people on the central park lawn, not only to track artists such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B or Shawn Mendes, but also to increase awareness of the true goal of the event, eliminating extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizens' Festival, launched in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international advocacy group that hopes to eliminate poverty by increasing the number of people fighting actively against it.
In order to receive a free ticket to the event (unless they are willing to pay for a VIP ticket), spectators had to pay for a series of tasks or “actions” such as volunteering, sending emails to world leaders, making telephone calls or other significant things that help increase the level of awareness of the goal of eliminating global poverty.
But what success has the Global Citizens' Festival had when there are only 12 years left to achieve the goal?
Is it the idea to reward people with a free concert a good way to convince them to act or is it just another case of so-called "clickivism", a concept that refers to people who feel they've made something by signing an online petition or sending a message on Twitter?
According to Global Citizen, in 2011 more than 19 million “actions” were registered from its supporters, who promoted different objectives.
The organization says these actions have driven world leaders to announce commitments and policies worth more than 37 billion dollars, which will affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group spoke of 390 commitments and announcements caused by its actions, in the account of which at least $10 billion was already spent or close.
The group estimates that the funds provided so far had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the key commitments are The Power of Nutrition, a partnership with headquarters in Britain of investors and intermediaries who have committed themselves to “helping children grow to their full potential”, which has promised to offer Rwanda $35 million to contribute to the elimination of malnutrition in the country, after receiving more than 4700 messages on Twitter from global citizens.
"With the help of the British government, donors, national governments and global citizens like you, we can make the social injustice of malnutrition become just a footnote in the history book," said Tracey Ulman, Ambassador The Power of Nutrition, in front of the crowd during a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that, after more than 5,000 actions have been carried out in Britain to improve the nutrition of mothers and children, the government announced that it will finance the The Power of Nutrition project, which will provide nutrition interventions for 5 million women and children.
The answer to one of the most frequently asked questions on their website: "What makes you think you can eliminate extreme poverty?"
Global Citizen replied: “It will be a long and difficult road, sometimes we will fall and fail.
But like the great moves for civil rights or anti-apartheid that took place before us, we will succeed, because together we are stronger.
