In order to justify capital punishment, prosecutors must prove that Saipov killed the eight victims “intentionally” and intentionally caused serious bodily injury, according to the intent of requesting capital punishment, filed in the New York Southern District.
Both counts of charges may receive a capital sentence, according to the court's document.
A few weeks after the attack, a large federal jury accused Saipov of 22 charges including eight criminal charges in support of organized crime, usually used by federal prosecutors in organised crime cases, as well as an accusation of violence and the destruction of motorized vehicles.
The attack required "substantial planning and premeditation", the prosecutors said, describing how Saipov executed the act as "hate, cruel and depraved".
“Sayfullo Habibullaevic Saipov caused injuries, sufferings and losses for the families and friends of the following people: Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laure Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erlij, Hernan Ferruchi, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnucco”, according to the notice of intent.
Five of the victims were tourists from Argentina.
It's been a decade since the last trial of a case of capital punishment in the New York Southern District.
The street, Khalid Barnes, was accused of killing two drug dealers, but he was finally sentenced to life in prison in September 2009.
The last capital punishment applied in a federal case in New York took place in 1953 for Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, two husbands executed after they were convicted of conspiracy to commit spying for the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
The Rosenberg wives were executed on the electric chair on June 19, 1953.
According to court documents, Saipov, a Uzbec citizen, showed no regret in the days and months after the attack.
He confessed to the investigators that he was happy with what he did, according to the police.
