How can the Beijing trade war between the United States and China be beneficial?
Saves that announced the start of the trade war between the United States and China were absurd and, although it seems to be a long way to end, disputes between the two countries could be beneficial to Beijing in the long term, experts say.
Donald Trump, President of the United States, issued the first warning earlier this year by imposing taxes on key imports from China, including solar panels, steel and aluminium.
The most important escalation occurred this week with new taxes, which affected products worth $200 billion (150 billion pounds), effectively applying taxes for half of all goods in China that reach the United States.
Beijing took revenge every time, most recently imposing a tax of between 5 and 10% for US products worth 60 billion dollars.
China has warned that it will respond to every blow from the United States and it is unlikely that the second largest economy of the world will take a step back in the near future.
In order for Washington to withdraw, China must agree with its requests, but publicly surrendering to the United States would be much too humiliating for Xi Jinping, president of China.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays cards well, US trade war pressures could positively support China in the long term, reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
"The fact that a quick political decision made in Washington or Beijing could lead to economic collapse in both countries would actually be more dangerous than what has been anticipated so far," said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher who focuses on Asia at the Center for a New American Security (Center for New American Security), a group of experts.
Syria is ready for the return of refugees, says Minister for Foreign Affairs
Syria claims it is prepared for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild the country devastated by a war that has lasted for more than seven years.
During his speech at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that the situation in the country is improving.
"Today the conditions on the site are more stable and secure, thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists so that things will return to normal.
Existing conditions allow the voluntary return of refugees to the country they were required to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and lives.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians fled the country in 2011, when the war broke out.
Six million people who continue to live in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to receive help in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he stressed that conditional assistance or aid from countries sponsored by insurgency would not be accepted.
